@Article{RussellWC2008,
  author           = {A. Wendy Russell and Fern Wickson and Anna L. Carew},
  date             = {2008},
  journaltitle     = {Futures},
  title            = {Transdisciplinarity: Context, contradictions and capacity},
  doi              = {https://doi.org/10.1016/j.futures.2007.10.005},
  issn             = {0016-3287},
  number           = {5},
  pages            = {460-472},
  url              = {https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0016328707001541},
  volume           = {40},
  abstract         = {Transdisciplinarity has been proposed as a response to the shifting knowledge landscape in contemporary society. It promises to bring universities and other knowledge organisations into line with new demands and opportunities. In this study, we have investigated drivers of change in the shifting landscape, and note disparate drivers that plot different courses for transdisciplinarity. We describe three drivers: `the knowledge economy', `the environmental imperative' and `the engaged populace'. We discuss their different prescriptions for transdisciplinary knowledge production and contradictions that arise from these, including tensions between consolidation and interconnection, and between knowledge commodification and mutual learning. In response, we suggest that rather than investing in knowledge `products', universities should focus on developing capacity for transdisciplinarity, and for knowledge production generally.},
  comment          = {Argue that commodification of knowledge endagers transdisciplinarity and knowledge production.

The shifting landscape of knowledge production:
- knowledge economy:

Knowledge economy emerging as feature of capitalism. Knowledge is seen as contributing to the economy by reshaping and adding value to existing industries and creating new industries. There is a reconceptualisation of knowledge as a commodity traded with knowledge consumers.

This is reflected in changes to university funding and incentives, ``third role'' to contribute to the economy and generate more funding for themselves and the ``corporatisation of universities'' - research priorities now being reorganized into a few research strengths and priority areas

Australian Cooperative Research Centre CRC is a response - universities with industry research partners

- environmental imperative:
Environmental imperative has seen more consideration of ideas of practice of transdisciplinarity

- engaged populace:
Education and knowledge are more socially distributed with www and higher amount of higher education

calls by Gibbons and co-workers for a shift to Mode 2 knowledge production, which is synonymous with transdisciplinarity]

``The tainting of some of the Mertonian norms of science - disinterestedness and objectivity - by values of the market and by the contingencies of application and past failings of science to adequately address complex and uncertain problems have also lead to challenges to the monopoly authority of science. This loss of authority, which has been described as a ``crisis of public confidence'', creates new opportunities for other sources of knowledge to gain legitimacy. This is supported by movements inside and outside academia challenging the dominance of scientific knowledge and promoting respect for diverse lay and indigenous knowledges. A lack of faith in the power of science to provide all the answers, or even to ask the right questions, has led to increasing demand for the public to be included in decision-making processes and for science to seek a `shared vision' or `contract' with the public'' [worth looking up refs in this section]

Engaged populace is a driver for transdisciplinarity

Where is the place of people in our knowledge?

``there are increasing demands for public participation in knowledge creation and policy deliberations, both from the bottom-up (i.e. from a more educated populace which lacks confidence in science) and from the top-down (i.e. from researchers and government who recognize the value of lay knowledge for decision quality). This translates into the need for an approach to knowledge production that is consultative, deliberative and participatory. This has given rise to the concept of mutual learning'' p464-5

Transdisciplinarity and multidisciplinary are seen as counter to formation of silos. But university consolidation with commercial incentives risks building mega silos. p465

``Transdisciplinarity is a practice that requires flexibility and fluidity. There are several ways in which attempts to institutionalise it may in fact inhibit it'': p466
1. mega-silos replace disciplinary boundaries with topic, technology and industry boundaries
2. institutions that have invested transdisciplinary approaches may be unresponsive to new problems - related to `paradox of density' which finds that innovation in a research area is proportionally greater when the area is new
3.  institutionalisation may detract from a knowledge production approach that provides interconnection, complexity and systems thinking e.g. interconnections between economic, environmental and social dimensions
4. can lead to reprioritisation around commercial agendas

Considers area of plant improvement - see what to commercialisable research but not in publications.

Contradictions and tensions:
- institutionalisation versus interconnection - ``institutionalisation threatening interconnection represents a tension between the `knowledge economy' perspective and the environmental imperative''
- knowledge commodification mutual learning - Commercialisation of knowledge and `resource extraction'
  - problem of power - privileging of particular types of knowledge
  - some scientists driven by knowledge economy and its opportunities, others fear threats to their autonomy

``Differences in intellectual property cultures, between academia and industry, but even more notably between formalised and lay or indigenous knowledge, leave open the prospect of exploitation of knowledge `resources' ''
Commodification of knowledge endagers transdisciplinarity and knowledge production - thus there is a need to build intellectual capacity in universities - . ``Strong intellectual capacity is therefore best served by combining disciplinarity and transdisciplinarity'' p469

Currently university ``culture is characterised by individuality, elitism, the accumulation of advantage (the Matthew effect) and academic territorialism associated with disciplines and specialisations'' p469-70},
  creationdate     = {2024-03-24T13:35:50},
  keywords         = {research,science,participatory,university,thesis},
  modificationdate = {2024-07-18T11:58:39},
  owner            = {izzy_olivine},
}

@Article{TurnhoutMWKL2020,
  author           = {Esther Turnhout and Tamara Metze and Carina Wyborn and Nicole Klenk and Elena Louder},
  date             = {2020},
  journaltitle     = {Current Opinion in Environmental Sustainability},
  title            = {The politics of co-production: participation, power, and transformation},
  doi              = {10.1016/j.cosust.2019.11.009},
  pages            = {15--21},
  url              = {https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1877343519301010},
  volume           = {42},
  comment          = {co-production literature has not paid sufficient attention to the role of power and politics in shaping processes and outcomes

key issue of representation: ``who participates and what values, perspectives and interests do these participants represent, and deliberation; how can all voices be voiced and included in a legitimate way''

biases towards elite actors are worrying because they result in these processes reproducing or even exacerbating existing inequalities. Elite actors (e.g. government, large NGOs, or scientists) are able to shape these processes to serve their interests because they:
- have more time and resources available
- often initiate these processes, define the scope for participation
- have more knowledge and skills
- better able to articulate a contribution that is considered relevant and important
- have strong authority that is attributed to scientific expertise vis-a-vis other knowledge systems p16
- often paid to participate as part of their professional roles, while the other participants are expected to volunteer their time
- more often invited to participate than unorganized citizens or less well-known groups

Further:
- inherent Western bias
- ongoing challenges of colonialism
- contexts characterized by conflict, and communities that are not able to self-organize nor given support by local decision-maker

Unequal power is often driven by depoliticisation which enforces norms in knowledge and communication which drives out other political interests, norms and values [- basically not mentioning the political elephant in the room -] Examples include ignore the lobbying effects of powerful interests.

Depoliticisation can be recognised as:
1. projects led by a rationale of science-driven impacts and do not challenge existing hierarchies between scientific and other knowledge holders
2. projects strive for consensus and for solutions that are considered rational according to elite perspectives, but which may cover up fundamental differences among participants in terms of stakes, power, access to resources, vulnerability, and risk
3. co-production stays confined to project boundaries without engaging the wider political context in which these projects are embedded

``co-production as both a knowledge-making and a political practice which is inevitably imbued with unequal power relations that need to be acknowledged but cannot be managed away''

``there are no simple solutions''},
  creationdate     = {2024-03-24T14:09:27},
  keywords         = {participatory,policy,design,power,thesis},
  modificationdate = {2024-05-06T16:45:26},
  owner            = {izzy_olivine},
}

@Article{PascualEtAl2018,
  author           = {Unai Pascual and Patricia Balvanera and Sandra D\'iaz and Gy\"orgy Pataki and Eva Roth and Marie Stenseke and Robert T. Watson and Esra {Başak Dessane} and Mine Islar and Eszter Kelemen and Virginie Maris and Martin Quaas and Suneetha M Subramanian and Heidi Wittmer and Asia Adlan and SoEun Ahn and Yousef S. Al-Hafedh and Edward Amankwah and Stanley T. Asah and Pam Berry and Adem Bilgin and Sara J. Breslow and Craig Bullock and Daniel C\'aceres and Hamed Daly-Hassen and Eugenio Figueroa and Christopher D Golden and Erik G\'omez-Baggethun and David González-Jiménez and Jo\"el Houdet and Hans Keune and Ritesh Kumar and Keping Ma and Peter H. May and Aroha Mead and Patrick O'Farrell and Ram Pandit and Walter Pengue and Ram\'on Pichis-Madruga and Florin Popa and Susan Preston and Diego Pacheco-Balanza and Heli Saarikoski and Bernardo B Strassburg and Marjan {van den Belt} and Madhu Verma and Fern Wickson and Noboyuki Yagi},
  date             = {2018},
  journaltitle     = {Current Opinion in Environmental Sustainability},
  title            = {Valuing nature's contributions to people: the IPBES approach},
  doi              = {https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cosust.2016.12.006},
  issn             = {1877-3435},
  note             = {Open issue, part II},
  number           = {27},
  pages            = {7--16},
  url              = {https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1877343517300040},
  volume           = {26},
  abstract         = {Nature is perceived and valued in starkly different and often conflicting ways. This paper presents the rationale for the inclusive valuation of nature's contributions to people (NCP) in decision making, as well as broad methodological steps for doing so. While developed within the context of the Intergovernmental Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services (IPBES), this approach is more widely applicable to initiatives at the knowledge-policy interface, which require a pluralistic approach to recognizing the diversity of values. We argue that transformative practices aiming at sustainable futures would benefit from embracing such diversity, which require recognizing and addressing power relationships across stakeholder groups that hold different values on human nature-relations and NCP.},
  comment          = {Nature's Contribution to People (NCP) bridges notions of nature and a good quality of life

Recognises that there are different worldviews and values associated with NCP and present the rationale for an inclusive incorporation of the diversity of values of NCP in decision making

Emphasis in the consideration of diverse values of NCP to inform policies and everyday practices can be placed, for example on:
- food and feed
