@Book{Killick2023,
  author           = {Killick, Anna},
  date             = {2023},
  title            = {Politicians and Economic Experts: The Limits of Technocracy},
  edition          = {1},
  isbn             = {1788215656},
  language         = {eng},
  location         = {Newcastle Upon Tyne},
  publisher        = {Agenda Publishing},
  url              = {https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/politicians-and-economic-experts/CB80182085E01CC8186F4F5FA97A66B0},
  abstract         = {In recent years politics has seen an increasing role in economic policy-making for a technocracy of experts. How do politicians feel about this and how do they balance their political and ethical aims with economic expertise?.},
  comment          = {Really interesting book based on findings of interviews with politicians about how they view and work with economists as experts. Underlying consideration is how economics expertise may be use for decisions related to the climate crisis.

Interviews are with 85 politicians from France, Denmark, Germany, UK and US, a range of polticial parties, some who've never been in government. Diverse perspectives are identified, largely along political lines. Also ``triangulated'' with politicians' advisors. Particularly interesting for the method - detailed in the appendix

Did not intruduce environment/climate into interview until late (if at all - it was not introduced for early interviews) to give a sense of how much these topics were considered to relate to the overt topic of economics.

Chapter 1 Do we need more economic experts?

Situates the book in the timing of COP26, noticing how many financial advisors to governments attended - awareness that climate has a strong financial/economic aspect. Introduces the suggestion by some for a new technocracy - previously right wing politicians have called for some aspects of the state to be ``depoliticised'' and passed on to relevant experts, privatised utilities - now there's a progressive call to use experts to advise on the climate and other crises. This could suit politicians who can blame others if it doesn't pan out.

Chapter 2 Politicians' respect for economists

Broad patterns within the interviews. Far-right parties resisted being interviewed. Economic goals are often expressed in a moralistic way - distributive justice and growth, so that people have the things they want. Analysed which economists were mentioned (elicited by indirect questions such as how useful they found exonomists) and found a quarter barely mentioned any. Questioned about economists objectivity - those with centre-right thinking about neoclassical mainstream economists were more likely that others to say they think they are objective and accepted economists as scientists to a degree. But more were sceptical about economists' objectivity. Many do not seem to respect the specialised knowledge of economists - finding them too technical or their advice impractical. Also politicians believe if is their own responsibliity to make decisions, some with advice from economists and other experts. Those economists/schools most respected are Keynes and Liberals, followed by Marx/Hayek/Free Market, then Adam Smith/Friedman/Council of economic advisors. Give a top-20 21st century economists positively cited (includes Behaviourl economists, Piketty, Rawaroth, Krugman, Mazzucato).

Chapter 8 Politicians and climate change economists

Given the results and what the interviewees said, what place economics expertise in tackling the climate emergency? Having not directly questioned about this, at least at the start, an indication about how much climate mattered could be gauged. Divergent ideas falling into 3 categories:
1. threat from climate change as only marginally affecting their economic ideas, either because they think the threat is not severe or because they think they can deal with it within their existing market-based economic paradigms, adaptation such as insurance is more valued than mitigation which may cause the economy to ``suffer''
2. modified their responses to a greater extent - a very large group that spans different approaches
3. environmentalism should become the basis for economic thinking - believing in ``socio-ecological restructuring''

far-left politicians who argue for radical environmentalist and social economic policies are divided into Marxist ``productivist'' (often embraced by trade unionists) and a more ``post-work'' orientation and opt for ``de-growth''

Sense the politicians have changed their perspectives a great deal, but environment is still ``tacked onto how they always thought about the economy'' this may not be so for future generations of politicians.

Discussion of how voters may not understand economic ideas, how heterodox left ideas are far from economic visions of self-interest voters,

Other chpateres go into more details on individual countries and politicians relationship to voters, including chapters on educating voters},
