@Book{WesselinkH2020,
  author           = {Anna Wesselink and Robert Hoppe},
  date             = {2020-08-27},
  title            = {Boundary Organizations: Intermediaries in Science-Policy Interactions},
  doi              = {10.1093/acrefore/9780190228637.013.1412},
  publisher        = {Oxford University Press},
  url              = {https://oxfordre.com/politics/view/10.1093/acrefore/9780190228637.001.0001/acrefore-9780190228637-e-1412},
  booktitle        = {Oxford Research Encyclopedia of Politics},
  comment          = {Constructivist approach to understanding boundary work as an endeavour within multiple levels in society. This ultimately explains why boundary organisations are not a ``silver bullet'' because their success depends on:
- the (inter)national political culture regarding the status and role of science in policymaking
- the culture of the policy domain
- the characteristics of the policy problem itself
- the role of the relevant boundary organization and its activities
- the framing of the policy problem (defines the need for science)
- path dependency is also evident from how the organisation was set up

`` it is not possible to formulate definitive prescriptions or `best practice' on boundary organizations or boundary work'' - but it seems difficult for boundary organisations to give up this goal

academic endeavours have three interwoven elements: 
- descriptive (“what is actually happening”)
- analytical (“how can we understand what is happening”)
- prescriptive (“how can we improve the situation”)

``closely intertwined because a researcher's descriptive, analytical, and normative perspectives on science-politics relations determine what (s)he observes, how (s)he analyses the observations and what prescriptions (s)he proposes''

Problem structuring theory - two dimensions:
- puzzling - expert side - certainty of knowledge
- powering - political/policy side - agreement on goals

 result in 4 types of problem:
 - structured problems - low puzzling low powering; akin to RittelW1073 tame problems
 - moderately structured problems, goals agreed - high puzzling low powering
 - moderately structured problems, means agreed - low puzzling high powering
 - unstructured problems - high puzzling high powering; akin to RittelW1973 wicked problems
 
 Boundary work has constrasting features:
 coordination between puzzling and powering to co-produce solutions - profane 
 demarcation between puzzling and powering to maintain objectivity - sacred
 
 [MidgleyMB1998 use the distinction between sacred and profane slightly differently but I wonder if they can be considered the same?]
 
Balancing act between credibility and usefulness
 
4 activities needed for policy problem processing (occur at multiple levels in society):
- problem framing
- problem structuring
- knowledge and actor selection
- regulating relations between science and society

levels in society, influence is between adjacent levels, each is described in detail:
1. macro-level - political-cultural sphere - determined by political culture and regulatory style - Renn created typology of these spheres
2. meso-level - policy problem networks - information, communication, resource and power result in networks specilising in particular policy issue - typology is based on problem structuring and uses policy coalition/community theories (see policy issue politics below)
3. boundary organizations - between professional-academic networks and public/policy organisation - 3 features: double participation, dual accountability, use of boundary objects
4. micro-level - policy advice and implementation projects - e.g. statements for policymakers from IPCC, CRELE model fits here

policy issue politics are structured using the puzzling/powering model, tensions arise if problem is dealt with in the wrong way (wrong-problem problem):
- structured problems - regulatory policy in closed professional/technical community
- moderately structured problems, goals agreed - advocacy coalition politics and/or problem-driven search, in oligopolistic policy subsystems
- moderately structured problems, means agreed - discourse coalition politics, accommodation strategies, or conflict management in designed issue network(s)
- unstructured problems - agenda-changing politics, crisis management; deliberation and learning in emergent network(s)

Failure to solve environmental crises is failure to to recognise that these are less structured problems (Funtowicz/Ravetz)

``There is overwhelming evidence that responses to (new) policy developments are influenced by political cultures and regulatory styles in the political-cultural sphere ... For example, Jordan, Benson, Wurzel, and Zito (2011) clearly show how policy instrument design in European climate change governance is strongly influenced by national policy styles and cultures''

Provides examples of boundary organisations:
- IPCC and IPBES - really interesting detail on IPCC, the other organisations that it is linked to and climategate
- UK: Tyndall Centre, CCC, Hadley Centre at Met Office
- also Germany, The Netherlands, US},
